<p>
    In simpler terms, a mealy machine is a finite state machine whose output is determined by current state and input.
    The inputs to the machine, in this case, are representative of messages sent by the bot to a botnet server. And the
    outputs representative of the botnet server&apos;s response.
</p>

<p>
    A modification to the L* algorithm
    <button type="button"
            class="btn btn-sm reference"
            data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="right"
            title="Dana Angluin. Learning regular sets from queries and counterexamples. Information and Computation, 75(2):87–106, 1987">
        [46],
    </button>

    allows for mealy machine inference provided there is some teacher that can confirm a correct proposition or respond
    with a counter example when supplied with a mealy machine

    <button type="button"
            class="btn btn-sm reference"
            data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="right"
            title="Muzammil Shahbaz and Roland Groz. Inferring Mealy machines. In FM’09: Proceedings of the 2nd World Congress on Formal Methods, pages 207–222, Berlin, Heidelberg, 2009. Springer.">
        [49].
    </button>

    In brief, queries are made to the teacher in the form of strings representing sequences of input who responds with
    strings representing sequences of output behaviour. The input and output strings are stored in an observation table.
    The algorithm processes the observation table and proposes a mealy machine to the teacher. The teacher replies with
    some counter-example that distinguishes the proposed mealy machine with the actual mealy machine.

</p>